                <section id="what-is-gan" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">1. What Is Gallium Nitride (GaN)? The Science Simplified</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">Gallium Nitride (GaN) is a <strong>wide-bandgap semiconductor</strong> — a crystalline material that conducts electricity under specific conditions while blocking it under others. It's the same class of material that makes LED lights possible. In chargers, GaN replaces the silicon transistors that have been the industry standard for over 60 years.</p>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">The key difference comes down to physics. GaN has a <strong>bandgap of 3.4 electronvolts (eV)</strong>, compared to silicon's 1.1 eV. This wider bandgap means GaN can handle higher voltages before breaking down, switch on and off at much higher frequencies, and do both with significantly less energy wasted as heat.</p>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 mb-6">
                        <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-4">The Bandgap Advantage — Why It Matters</h3>
                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 text-center">
                            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5">
                                <div class="text-3xl font-black text-brandBlue mb-2">3.4 eV</div>
                                <div class="text-xs text-slate-500 uppercase tracking-wider">GaN Bandgap</div>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-2">Handles higher voltages without breakdown. Enables compact designs.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5">
                                <div class="text-3xl font-black text-slate-400 mb-2">1.1 eV</div>
                                <div class="text-xs text-slate-500 uppercase tracking-wider">Silicon Bandgap</div>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-2">Lower threshold means more energy lost as heat during conversion.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5">
                                <div class="text-3xl font-black text-brandOrange mb-2">3×</div>
                                <div class="text-xs text-slate-500 uppercase tracking-wider">GaN Advantage</div>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-2">Three times wider bandgap = fundamentally better power handling.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">Think of it this way: silicon is like a narrow country road — it works, but traffic slows down when too many cars try to pass. GaN is like a multi-lane highway — electrons move faster, with less congestion (resistance), and less energy wasted as heat. This is why GaN chargers can be simultaneously <strong>smaller, cooler, and more powerful</strong> than their silicon counterparts.</p>
                    <p class="text-slate-600">According to <a href="https://epc-co.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:underline">Efficient Power Conversion (EPC)</a>, a leading GaN semiconductor manufacturer, GaN transistors can switch at frequencies 100× faster than silicon MOSFETs while achieving power conversion efficiency exceeding 99% in optimized designs.</p>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section id="how-it-works" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">2. How Do GaN Chargers Work?</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">A charger's job is to convert the alternating current (AC) from your wall outlet into the direct current (DC) your device needs. This conversion happens inside a component called a <strong>switched-mode power supply</strong>, where transistors rapidly switch on and off to regulate voltage and current.</p>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">Traditional silicon transistors switch at frequencies of <strong>100-500 kHz</strong>. GaN transistors switch at <strong>1-10 MHz</strong> — up to 100× faster. This higher switching frequency is the root cause of every GaN advantage:</p>
                    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
                        <div class="flex gap-4">
                            <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-brandBlue rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-black shrink-0">1</div>
                            <div>
                                <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Faster Switching = Smaller Components</h3>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Higher frequency means the charger's transformer and capacitors can be physically smaller while handling the same power. This is why a 65W GaN charger is roughly the size of a credit card stack, while a 65W silicon charger is a palm-sized brick.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="flex gap-4">
                            <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-brandBlue rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-black shrink-0">2</div>
                            <div>
                                <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Less Energy Lost as Heat</h3>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">In a silicon charger, roughly 15-20% of input power becomes waste heat. In a GaN charger, only 3-5% is lost. Less waste heat means no need for bulky heat sinks and safer long-term operation.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="flex gap-4">
                            <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-brandBlue rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-black shrink-0">3</div>
                            <div>
                                <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Higher Power Density</h3>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Power density measures how much wattage fits in a given volume. GaN achieves 1.5-2W per cubic centimeter vs silicon's 0.5-0.8W/cc — packing 2-3× more power into the same space.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- GaN Charger Product Image -->
                    <div class="mb-6">
                        <img src="/image/blog/gan-charger/gan-charger-800x800.webp"
                        alt="WOWOHCOOL GaN charger - compact 65W Gallium Nitride fast charger with USB-C PD port"
