                    </div>

                    <div class="bg-brandBlue/10 border-l-4 border-brandBlue p-6 rounded-r-xl">
                        <h4 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">GaN ≠ PD (Power Delivery) — A Common Confusion</h4>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">GaN is a <strong>hardware material</strong> (the semiconductor inside the charger). PD (Power Delivery) is a <strong>software protocol</strong> (how the charger and device negotiate power). They work together — a GaN charger typically supports USB PD — but they are fundamentally different things. You can have a GaN charger without PD, and a PD charger without GaN. The 2026 industry standard is <strong>GaN + PD 3.1 + PPS</strong> — all three working in concert.</p>
                    </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section id="benefits" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">3. Key Benefits of GaN Chargers</h2>
                    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">40-50% Smaller Size</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">A 65W GaN charger is roughly the size of a deck of cards. The same wattage in silicon is a palm-sized brick. This makes GaN ideal for travel, commuting, and minimalist desk setups. Manufacturers can fit more power into less space because GaN's higher switching frequency allows smaller internal components.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">30% Cooler Operation</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Lower energy loss means less heat. A GaN charger under full load runs measurably cooler than silicon equivalents. This isn't just about comfort — lower temperatures extend component lifespan and reduce the risk of thermal throttling, where the charger slows down to protect itself.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">95%+ Energy Efficiency</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">GaN chargers convert 95-97% of wall power into usable charging power, compared to 80-85% for silicon. For a 65W charger, that's the difference between ~3W wasted (GaN) and ~10W wasted (silicon). Over thousands of charging cycles, the energy savings add up significantly.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">Up to 240W Power Delivery</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">GaN's superior thermal properties make high-wattage compact chargers possible. While silicon chargers top out around 65-100W in a portable form factor, GaN chargers reach 140W-240W — enough to fast-charge gaming laptops and workstations from a pocket-sized adapter.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-xl p-6">
                        <h4 class="font-black text-green-700 uppercase mb-3">Environmental Impact</h4>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Higher efficiency means less grid electricity wasted. If every charger worldwide switched from silicon to GaN, the cumulative energy savings would be measured in terawatt-hours annually. GaN chargers also last 2-3× longer than silicon equivalents, reducing electronic waste. According to <a href="https://www.yolegroup.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:underline">Yole Group</a>, GaN technology in power applications could save 2-3 million tons of CO₂ annually by 2027.</p>
                    </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section id="power-levels" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">4. GaN Charger Power Levels: 20W to 240W</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">GaN technology spans the full range from phone chargers to workstation power supplies. Here's what each tier delivers:</p>
                    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
                        <table class="w-full border border-slate-200 rounded-xl">
